              "inline_data": null,
              "text": "```text\nTHE LAW OF SINES\n\nThe Law of Sines is a trigonometric rule used to find the missing sides or angles of any triangle, not just right-angled triangles. It states that the ratio of the length of a side to the sine of its opposite angle is constant for all three sides of the triangle.\n\nTHE FORMULA:\n\na / sin(A) = b / sin(B) = c / sin(C)\n\nIn this formula:\n- a, b, and c represent the lengths of the sides of the triangle.\n- A, B, and C represent the angles opposite to sides a, b, and c respectively.\n\nWHEN TO USE IT:\n1. When you know two angles and one side (AAS or ASA).\n2. When you know two sides and an angle opposite one of those sides (SSA).\n```",
